templateAssets.content:
Engineering Geology is an interdisciplinary field that uses the principles of geologic processes to solve engineering and environmental problems. We provide coursework to evaluate possible geologic hazards and Earth structures (e.g., landslides, earthquake damage, structural geology, groundwater) and prepare for registered engineering professionals with geotechnical, geologic, and petroleum specialties.


Listed below are the lower division preparation courses for the major.


To be considered for this major, you must complete the following preparatory courses by the end of spring before transfer:

  • One introductory course in Earth Sciences with lab,
  • Two General Chemistry courses with Lab for majors, and
  • One year of Calculus.

A second semester of calculus-based physics with lab is STRONGLY RECOMMENDED.

All courses must be taken for a letter grade.


For more information regarding this major and UCLA's transfer selection process, visit https://epss.ucla.edu and https://admission.ucla.edu.


PLEASE NOTE: the community college courses listed below have been approved to satisfy the preparation requirement for this major at UCLA, but they may not be exact equivalents of the UCLA courses listed.
A semester of calculus based physics with lab is recommended.
